Weevil Genotypes

We used PCAngsd to call genotypes while taking genetic covariance into acount. Here we will load these genotype calls, filter loci by missing data and format data as required by BEDASSLE 2.0.

We will need two packages to manipulate data: reticulate to read the numpy matrices output by PCAngsd and tidyverse to manipulate data in R. We will also import the python module numpy:

library(tidyverse)
library(reticulate)
library(bedassle)
np = import("numpy", convert=FALSE)

Lets first load the table with sample data:

sample_data = readr::read_csv('weevil_data.csv',guess_max = 1000)
Missing column names filled in: 'X1' [1]
sample_data

As an example, we will now get counts for one species. At the end, we will encapsulate everything in a function and replicate for all species.

Lets start with the species name:

species = 'M_bondari_1'

Now, lets retrieve genotypes for this species as a matrix using reticulate. We will tranpose the matrix so that we have samples on columns and loci on rows.

gen_path = file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA',species,'*.geno.npy') %>%
  Sys.glob()
genotypes = np$load(gen_path) %>% 
  as.matrix() %>%
  t

Now, lets place sample names in columns, tranform in data frame and add a column with locus ID. We will also replace -9 with NA to represent missing data.

We can get the samples that were passed to ANGSD using the list of bam files.

bamfile = file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA',species,'bam.filelist')
samples = readr::read_lines(bamfile) %>% basename() %>% str_remove('\\..+$')
str(samples)
 chr [1:23] "BdM1211" "BdM1212" "BdM1213" "BdM1214" "BdM1215" "BdM1216" ...

Now lets read site names:

site_path = file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA',species,'*pca.sites') %>% 
  Sys.glob()
sites = readr::read_lines(site_path)
str(sites)
 chr [1:15973] "100_58" "100_61" "1000_31" "1000_57" "10001_8" "10001_57" ...

Now lets join samples, loci and genotypes in a single data.frame:

colnames(genotypes) = samples
genotypes = genotypes %>% 
  as_tibble %>%
  na_if(-9) %>%
  mutate(site = sites)
genotypes

Now, lets reshape this data.frame so we can add population information:

genotypes = genotypes %>%
  gather(key=sample,value=genotype,-site)
genotypes

We are getting there. Now lets add population information from the sample info data.frame:

genotypes = sample_data %>% 
  select(sample=genomics,population=pop_id_thesis) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  right_join(genotypes) %>%
  mutate(locus = str_remove(site, '_.+$') %>% as.integer)
Joining, by = "sample"

Now we have all of the data we need, lets filter SNPs. We will retain only one SNP per locus to avoid linked sites, selecting the SNP with least missing data for each locus (and randomly if there is a draw). We will choose a random seed to make this repeatable. Lets start by selecting SNPs:

set.seed(20405)
sites_to_keep = genotypes %>%
  group_by(locus,site) %>%
  summarise(Nmissing=sum(is.na(genotype)),
            no_SNP=sum(genotype,na.rm=T) == 0) %>%
  filter(Nmissing == min(Nmissing),
         no_SNP != TRUE) %>%
  sample_n(1) %>%
  pull(site)

Now lets keep only sites which were genotyped in all populations

sites_to_keep = genotypes %>%
  filter(site %in% sites_to_keep) %>%
  group_by(site,population) %>%
  summarise(all_missing=all(is.na(genotype))) %>%
  group_by(site) %>%
  summarise(any_pop_missing = any(all_missing)) %>%
  filter(!any_pop_missing) %>%
  pull(site)

Finally, lets apply filters and shape the data again as a matrix:

genotypes = genotypes %>%
  filter(site %in% sites_to_keep) %>%
  arrange(sample,site) 
freqs = genotypes %>%
  select(site,sample,genotype) %>%
  spread(key = sample, value = genotype) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-site) %>%
  as.matrix %>%
  t()

The above was just an example to visualize how this is done, lets now put all operations in a function and retrieve counts and sizes for all species:

get_allele_counts = function(species){
  gen_path = file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA',species,'*.geno.npy') %>%
  Sys.glob()
genotypes = np$load(gen_path) %>% 
  as.matrix() %>%
  t
  
bamfile = file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA',species,'bam.filelist')
samples = readr::read_lines(bamfile) %>% basename() %>% str_remove('\\..+$')
site_path = file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA',species,'*pca.sites')  %>% 
  Sys.glob()
sites = readr::read_lines(site_path)
colnames(genotypes) = samples
genotypes = genotypes %>% 
  as_tibble %>%
  na_if(-9) %>%
  mutate(site = sites)
  
genotypes = genotypes %>%
  gather(key=sample,value=genotype,-site)
genotypes = sample_data %>% 
  select(sample=genomics,population=pop_id_thesis) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  right_join(genotypes) %>%
  mutate(locus = str_remove(site, '_.+$') %>% as.integer)
  
sites_to_keep = genotypes %>%
  group_by(locus,site) %>%
  summarise(Nmissing=sum(is.na(genotype)),
            no_SNP=sum(genotype,na.rm=T) == 0) %>%
  filter(Nmissing == min(Nmissing),
         no_SNP != TRUE) %>%
  sample_n(1) %>%
  pull(site)
  
sites_to_keep = genotypes %>%
  filter(site %in% sites_to_keep) %>%
  group_by(site,population) %>%
  summarise(all_missing=all(is.na(genotype))) %>%
  group_by(site) %>%
  summarise(any_pop_missing = any(all_missing)) %>%
  filter(!any_pop_missing) %>%
  pull(site)
  
genotypes = genotypes %>%
  filter(site %in% sites_to_keep) %>%
  arrange(sample,site) 
freqs = genotypes %>%
  select(site,sample,genotype) %>%
  spread(key = sample, value = genotype) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-site) %>%
  as.matrix %>%
  t()
pairwisepi = bedassle::freqs2pairwisePi(freqs = freqs/2)
  
return(list(freqs = freqs,pi = pairwisepi))
}

Now lets apply this function to all species. Again, we will set a random seed to make sure random choices are reproducible.

#the first element is the main dir, so we remove it
species = list.dirs(file.path('..','ANGSD_weevils','PCA'),
                    full.names = F,
                    recursive = F)
names(species) = species
set.seed(1463713)
BEDASSLE_data = purrr::map(species,get_allele_counts)
